<para xml:id="C18.S3.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="1" xml:id="C18.S3.p1.s1">
Table 18.3.1 provides the definitions of Jacobi, Laguerre, and Hermite polynomials via orthogonality and normalization (§§18.2(i)and 18.2(iii)).
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="2" xml:id="C18.S3.p1.s2">
This table also includes the following special cases of Jacobi polynomials: ultraspherical, Chebyshev, and Legendre.
</sentence>

</para>
          
<sentence sentence-num-in-section="3" xml:id="C18.S3.T1.s1">
Table 18.3.1: Orthogonality properties for classical OP’s: intervals, weight functions, normalizations, leading coefficients, and parameter constraints. In the second row <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S3.T1.m1">\mathcal{A}_{n}</Math> denotes <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S3.T1.m2">\ifrac{2^{\alpha+\beta+1}\Gamma\left(n+\alpha+1\right)\Gamma\left(n+\beta+1 \right)}{((2n+\alpha+\beta+1)\Gamma\left(n+\alpha+\beta+1\right)n!)</Math>} , with <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C18.S3.T1.m3">\mathcal{A}_{0}=\ifrac{2^{\alpha+\beta+1}\Gamma\left(\alpha+1\right)\Gamma \left(\beta+1\right)}{\Gamma\left(\alpha+\beta+2\right)}</Math> . For further implications of the parameter constraints see the in § .
</sentence>
                  
                       

